1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROTECT NORTH CAROLINIANS BY ENACTING THE PERSONAL DATA
3 PRIVACY ACT AND SOCIAL MEDIA SAFETY ACT.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. ENACT PERSONAL DATA PRIVACY ACT
7 SECTION 1.1. This act shall be known and may be cited as the "North Carolina
8 Personal Data Privacy Act."
9 SECTION 1.2. Effective January 1, 2026, the General Statutes are amended by
10 adding a new Chapter to read:
11 "Chapter 75F.
12 "Data Privacy Act.
13 "§ 75F-101. Short title.
14 This Chapter shall be known and may be cited as the "North Carolina Data Privacy Act."
15 "§ 75F-102. Definitions.
16 The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
17 (1) Affiliate. – A legal entity that shares common branding with another legal
18 entity or controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with another
19 legal entity. For the purposes of this subdivision, "control" or "controlled"
20 means any of the following:
21 a. Ownership of, or the power to vote, more than fifty percent (50%) of
22 the outstanding shares of any class of voting security of a legal entity.
23 b. Control in any manner over the election of a majority of the directors
24 or of individuals exercising similar functions.
25 c. The power to exercise controlling influence over the management of a
26 legal entity.
27 (2) Authenticate. – To use reasonable means to determine that a request to
28 exercise any of the rights afforded under G.S. 75F-104(a)(1) to (4), inclusive,
29 is being made by, or on behalf of, the consumer who is entitled to exercise the
30 consumer rights with respect to the personal data at issue.
31 (3) Biometric data. – Personal information and data generated by automatic
32 measurements of an individual's unique biological characteristics, such as a
33 fingerprint, a voiceprint, eye retinas, irises, or other unique biological patterns
*H462-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 or characteristics that can be used to identify or authenticate a specific
2 individual. "Biometric data" does not include any of the following:
3 a. A digital or physical photograph.
4 b. An audio or video recording.
5 c. Any data generated from a digital or physical photograph, or an audio
6 or video recording, unless the data is generated to identify a specific
7 individual.
8 (4) Business associate. – As defined in HIPAA.
9 (5) Child. – As defined in COPPA.
10 (6) Child abuse. – With respect to an individual under 18 years of age, as defined
11 in Chapter 14 of the General Statutes or any equivalent provision in the laws
12 of any other state; the United States; any territory, district, or subdivision of
13 the United States; or any foreign jurisdiction.
14 (7) Consent. – A clear affirmative act signifying a consumer's freely given,
15 specific, informed, and unambiguous agreement to allow the processing of
16 personal data relating to the consumer. "Consent" may include a written
17 statement, including by electronic means, or any other unambiguous
18 affirmative action. "Consent" does not include any of the following:
19 a. Acceptance of a general or broad terms of use or similar document that
20 contains descriptions of personal data processing along with other,
21 unrelated information.
22 b. Hovering over, muting, pausing, or closing a given piece of content.
23 c. Agreement obtained through the use of dark patterns.
24 (8) Consumer. – An individual who is a resident of this State. "Consumer" does
25 not include an individual acting in a commercial or employment context or as
26 an employee, owner, director, officer, or contractor of a company, partnership,
27 sole proprietorship, nonprofit organization, or government agency whose
28 communications or transactions with the controller occur solely within the
29 context of that individual's role with the company, partnership, sole
30 proprietorship, nonprofit organization, or government agency.
31 (9) Controller. – A person that, alone or jointly with others, determines the
32 purpose and means of processing personal data.
33 (10) COPPA. – The Children's Online Privacy Protection Act of 1998, 15 U.S.C.
34 § 6501, et seq., as amended, and the regulations, rules, guidance, and
35 exemptions adopted pursuant to the act, and such regulations, rules, guidance,
36 and exemptions as may be amended.
37 (11) Covered entity. – As defined in HIPAA.
38 (12) Dark pattern. – Any of the following:
39 a. A user interface designed or manipulated with the substantial effect of
40 subverting or impairing user autonomy, decision making, or choice.
41 b. Any other practice the Federal Trade Commission refers to as a dark
42 pattern.
43 (13) Decisions that produce legal or similarly significant effects concerning the
44 consumer. – Decisions made by the controller that result in the provision or
45 denial by the controller of financial or lending services, housing, insurance,
46 education enrollment or opportunity, criminal justice, employment
47 opportunities, health care services, or access to essential goods or services.
48 (14) De-identified data. – Data that cannot reasonably be used to infer information
49 about, or otherwise be linked to, an identified or identifiable individual, or a
50 device linked to the individual, if the controller that possesses the data does
51 all of the following:
Page 2 House Bill 462-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. Takes reasonable measures to ensure that the data cannot be associated
2 with an individual.
3 b. Publicly commits to process the data only in a de-identified fashion
4 and not attempt to re-identify the data.
5 c. Contractually obligates any recipients of the data to comply with all of
6 the provisions of this Chapter applicable to the controller with respect
7 to the data.
8 (15) Domestic violence. - As defined in Chapter 14 of the General Statutes or any
9 equivalent provision in the laws of any other state; the United States; any
10 territory, district, or subdivision of the United States; or any foreign
11 jurisdiction.
12 (16) Genetic data. – Any data, regardless of its format, that results from the analysis
13 of a biological sample of an individual, or from another source enabling
14 equivalent information to be obtained, and concerns genetic material. For
15 purposes of this subdivision, "genetic material" includes deoxyribonucleic
16 acids (DNA), ribonucleic acids (RNA), genes, chromosomes, alleles,
17 genomes, alterations or modifications to DNA or RNA, single nucleotide
18 polymorphisms (SNPs), uninterpreted data that results from analysis of the
19 biological sample or other source, and any information extrapolated, derived,
20 or inferred therefrom.
21 (17) HIPAA. – The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996,
22 42 U.S.C. § 1320d, et seq., as amended.
23 (18) Human trafficking. – The offense defined in Chapter 14 of the General
24 Statutes or any equivalent provision in the laws of any other state; the United
25 States; any territory, district, or subdivision of the United States; or any
26 foreign jurisdiction.
27 (19) Identified or identifiable individual. – An individual who can be readily
28 identified, directly or indirectly.
29 (20) Nonprofit organization. – Any organization that is exempt from taxation under
30 section 501(c)(3), 501(c)(4), 501(c)(6), or 501(c)(12) of the Internal Revenue
31 Code of 1986, or any subsequent corresponding internal revenue code of the
32 United States, as amended.
33 (21) Personal data. – Any information that is linked or reasonably linkable to an
34 identified or identifiable individual and does not include de-identified data or
35 publicly available information.
36 (22) Precise geolocation data. – Information derived from technology, including
37 global positioning system level latitude and longitude coordinates or other
38 mechanisms, that directly identifies the specific location of an individual with
39 precision and accuracy within a radius of 1,750 feet. "Precise geolocation
40 data" does not include the content of communications or any data generated
41 by or connected to advanced utility metering infrastructure systems or
42 equipment for use by a utility.
43 (23) Process or processing. – Any operation or set of operations performed,
44 whether by manual or automated means, on personal data or on sets of
45 personal data, such as the collection, use, storage, disclosure, analysis,
46 deletion, or modification of personal data.
47 (24) Processor. – A person that processes personal data on behalf of a controller.
48 (25) Profiling. – Any form of automated processing performed on personal data to
49 evaluate, analyze, or predict personal aspects related to an identified or
50 identifiable individual's economic situation, health, demographic
House Bill 462-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 characteristics, personal preferences, interests, reliability, behavior, location,
2 or movements.
3 (26) Protected health information. – As defined in HIPAA.
4 (27) Pseudonymous data. – Personal data that cannot be attributed to a specific
5 individual without the use of additional information, provided the additional
6 information is kept separately and is subject to appropriate technical and
7 organizational measures to ensure that the personal data is not attributed to an
8 identified or identifiable individual.
9 (28) Publicly available information. – Information that is lawfully made readily
10 available to the general public through federal, State, or local government
11 records or widely distributed media and a controller has a reasonable basis to
12 believe a consumer has lawfully made readily available to the general public.
13 (29) Sale of personal data. – The exchange or transfer of personal data for monetary
14 or other valuable consideration by the controller to a third party. "Sale of
15 personal data" does not include any of the following:
16 a. The disclosure of personal data to a processor that processes the
17 personal data on behalf of the controller where limited to the purpose
18 of the processing.
19 b. The disclosure of personal data to a third party for purposes of
20 providing a product or service affirmatively requested by the
21 consumer.
22 c. The disclosure or transfer of personal data to an affiliate of the
23 controller.
24 d. The disclosure of personal data where the consumer directs the
25 controller to disclose the personal data or intentionally uses the
26 controller to interact with a third party.
27 e. The disclosure of personal data that the consumer intentionally made
28 available to the general public via a channel of mass media and did not
29 restrict to a specific audience.
30 f. The disclosure or transfer of personal data to a third party as an asset
31 that is part of a merger, acquisition, bankruptcy, or other similar
32 transaction in which the third party assumes control of all or part of
33 the controller's assets, or a proposed merger, acquisition, bankruptcy,
34 or other similar transaction in which the third party assumes control of
35 all or part of the controller's assets.
36 (30) Sensitive data. – Personal data that includes any of the following:
37 a. Data revealing racial or ethnic origin, religious beliefs, mental or
38 physical health condition or diagnosis (including pregnancy), sex life,
39 sexual orientation, status as transgender or nonbinary, national origin,
40 citizenship status, or immigration status.
41 b. Genetic or biometric data.
42 c. Personal data of a known child.
43 d. Precise geolocation data.
44 (31) Sexual assault. – Any of the offenses defined in Chapter 14 of the General
45 Statutes or any equivalent provision in the laws of any other state; the United
46 States; any territory, district, or subdivision of the United States; or any
47 foreign jurisdiction.
48 (32) Stalking. – The offense defined in Chapter 14 of the General Statutes or any
49 equivalent provision in the laws of any other state; the United States; any
50 territory, district, or subdivision of the United States; or any foreign
51 jurisdiction.
