41 (13) Personal data of a victim of or witness to child abuse, domestic violence,
42 human trafficking, sexual assault, violent felony, or stalking that is collected,
43 processed, or maintained by a nonprofit organization that provides services to
44 victims of or witnesses to child abuse, domestic violence, human trafficking,
45 sexual assault, violent felony, or stalking.
46 (d) Controllers and processors that comply with the verifiable parental consent
47 requirements of COPPA shall be deemed compliant with any obligation to obtain parental
48 consent set forth in this Chapter with respect to a consumer who is a child.
49 "§ 75F-104. Consumer personal data rights.
50 (a) A consumer has the right to do all of the following:
Page 6 House Bill 462-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Confirm whether a controller is processing the consumer's personal data and
2 access the personal data, unless the confirmation or access would require the
3 controller to reveal a trade secret.
4 (2) Correct inaccuracies in the consumer's personal data, taking into account the
5 nature of the personal data and the purposes of the processing of the
6 consumer's personal data.
7 (3) Have personal data provided by, or obtained about, the consumer deleted.
8 (4) Obtain a copy of the consumer's personal data processed by the controller, in
9 a portable and, to the extent technically feasible, readily usable format that
10 allows the consumer to transmit the data to another controller without
11 hindrance, where the processing is carried out by automated means, provided
12 the controller shall not be required to reveal any trade secret.
13 (5) Obtain a list of the specific third parties to which the controller has disclosed
14 the consumer's personal data. If the controller does not maintain this
15 information in a format specific to the consumer, a list of specific third parties
16 to whom the controller has disclosed any consumers' personal data may be
17 provided instead.
18 (6) Opt out of the processing of the personal data for purposes of any of the
19 following:
20 a. Targeted advertising.
21 b. The sale of personal data, except as provided in G.S. 75F-106(b).
22 c. Profiling in furtherance of solely automated decisions that produce
23 legal or similarly significant effects concerning the consumer.
24 (b) A consumer may exercise rights under this section by secure and reliable means
25 established by the controller and described to the consumer in the controller's privacy notice. A
26 consumer may designate an authorized agent in accordance with G.S. 75F-105 to exercise the
27 rights of the consumer to opt out of the processing of the consumer's personal data for purposes
28 of subdivision (5) of subsection (a) of this section on behalf of the consumer. In the case of
29 processing personal data of a known child, the parent or legal guardian may exercise the
30 consumer rights on the child's behalf. In the case of processing personal data concerning a
31 consumer subject to a guardianship, conservatorship, or other protective arrangement, the
32 guardian or the conservator of the consumer may exercise the rights on the consumer's behalf.
33 (c) Except as otherwise provided in this Chapter, a controller shall comply with a request
34 by a consumer to exercise the consumer rights authorized pursuant to said sections as follows:
35 (1) A controller shall respond to the consumer without undue delay but not later
36 than 45 days after receipt of the request. The controller may extend the
37 response period by 45 additional days when reasonably necessary, considering
38 the complexity and number of the consumer's requests, provided the controller
39 informs the consumer of any such extension within the initial 45-day response
40 period and of the reason for the extension.
41 (2) If a controller declines to take action regarding the consumer's request, the
42 controller shall inform the consumer without undue delay but not later than 45
43 days after receipt of the request of the justification for declining to take action
44 and instructions for how to appeal the decision.
45 (3) Information provided in response to a consumer request shall be provided by
46 a controller, free of charge, once per consumer during any 12-month period.
47 If requests from a consumer are manifestly unfounded, excessive, or
48 repetitive, the controller may charge the consumer a reasonable fee to cover
49 the administrative costs of complying with the request or decline to act on the
50 request. The controller bears the burden of demonstrating the manifestly
51 unfounded, excessive, or repetitive nature of the request.
