1 (4) If a controller is unable to authenticate a request to exercise any of the rights
2 afforded under subdivisions (1) through (5), inclusive, of subsection (a) of this
3 section using commercially reasonable efforts, the controller shall not be
4 required to comply with a request to initiate an action pursuant to this section
5 and shall provide notice to the consumer that the controller is unable to
6 authenticate the request to exercise the right or rights until the consumer
7 provides additional information reasonably necessary to authenticate the
8 consumer and the consumer's request to exercise the right or rights. A
9 controller shall not be required to authenticate an opt-out request, but a
10 controller may deny an opt-out request if the controller has a good-faith,
11 reasonable, and documented belief that the request is fraudulent. If a controller
12 denies an opt-out request because the controller believes the request is
13 fraudulent, the controller shall send a notice to the person who made the
14 request disclosing that the controller believes the request is fraudulent, why
15 the controller believes the request is fraudulent, and that the controller shall
16 not comply with the request.
17 (5) A controller that has obtained personal data about a consumer from a source
18 other than the consumer shall be deemed in compliance with a consumer's
19 request to delete the data pursuant to subdivision (3) of subsection (a) of this
20 section if the controller retains a record of the deletion request and the
21 minimum data necessary for the purpose of ensuring the consumer's personal
22 data remains deleted from the controller's records and does not use the retained
23 data for any other purpose.
24 (d) A controller shall establish a process for a consumer to appeal the controller's refusal
25 to take action on a request within a reasonable period of time after the consumer's receipt of the
26 decision. The appeal process shall be conspicuously available and similar to the process for
27 submitting requests to initiate action pursuant to this section. Not later than 60 days after receipt
28 of an appeal, a controller shall inform the consumer in writing of any action taken or not taken
29 in response to the appeal, including a written explanation of the reasons for the decisions. If the
30 appeal is denied, the controller shall also provide the consumer with an online mechanism, if
31 available, or other method through which the consumer may contact the Department of Justice
32 to submit a complaint.
33 "§ 75F-105. Designation of agent to exercise rights of consumer, including through
34 universal opt-out mechanisms.
35 (a) A consumer may designate an authorized agent to act on the consumer's behalf to opt
36 out of the processing of the consumer's personal data for one or more of the purposes specified
37 in G.S. 75F-104(a)(5). The consumer may designate the authorized agent by way of, among other
38 things, a platform, technology, or mechanism, including an internet link or a browser setting,
39 browser extension, or global device setting, indicating the consumer's intent to opt out of the
40 processing. For the purposes of the designation, the platform, technology, or mechanism may
41 function as the agent for purposes of conveying the consumer's decision to opt out.
42 (b) A controller shall comply with an opt-out request received from an authorized agent
43 if the controller is able to verify, with commercially reasonable effort, the identity of the
44 consumer and the authorized agent's authority to act on the consumer's behalf. The Department
45 of Justice may publish or reference on its website a list of agents who presumptively shall have
46 the authority unless the controller has established a reasonable basis to conclude that the agent
47 lacks such authority.
48 "§ 75F-106. Duties of controllers.
49 (a) A controller shall do all of the following:
Page 8 House Bill 462-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Limit the collection of personal data to what is adequate, relevant, and
2 reasonably necessary in relation to the purposes for which the data is
3 processed, as disclosed to the consumer.
4 (2) Except as otherwise permitted by this Chapter, not process personal data for
5 purposes that are neither reasonably necessary to, nor compatible with, the
6 disclosed purposes for which the personal data is processed, as disclosed to
7 the consumer, unless the controller obtains the consumer's consent.
8 (3) Establish, implement, and maintain reasonable administrative, technical, and
9 physical data security practices to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and
10 accessibility of personal data appropriate to the volume and nature of the
11 personal data at issue.
12 (4) Not process sensitive data concerning a consumer without obtaining the
13 consumer's consent or, in the case of the processing of sensitive data
14 concerning a known child, without first obtaining consent from the child's
15 parent or lawful guardian.
16 (5) Not process personal data in violation of the laws of this State and federal laws
17 that prohibit unlawful discrimination.
18 (6) Provide an effective mechanism for a consumer to revoke the consumer's
19 consent under this section that is at least as easy as the mechanism by which
20 the consumer provided the consumer's consent and, upon revocation of the
21 consent, cease to process the data as soon as practicable but not later than 15
22 days after the receipt of the request.
23 (7) Not process the personal data of a consumer for purposes of targeted
24 advertising, or sell the consumer's personal data without the consumer's
25 consent, under circumstances where a controller has actual knowledge or
26 willfully disregards that the consumer is at least 13 years of age but younger
27 than 18 years of age.
28 (8) Not discriminate against a consumer for exercising any of the consumer rights
29 contained in this Chapter, including denying goods or services, charging
30 different prices or rates for goods or services, or providing a different level of
31 quality of goods or services to the consumer.
32 (b) Nothing in subsection (a) of this section shall be construed to require a controller to
33 provide a product or service that requires the personal data of a consumer which the controller
34 does not collect or maintain, or prohibit a controller from offering a different price, rate, level,
35 quality, or selection of goods or services to a consumer, including offering goods or services for
36 no fee, if the offering is in connection with a consumer's voluntary participation in a bona fide
37 loyalty, rewards, premium features, discounts, or club card program.
38 (c) A controller shall provide consumers with a reasonably accessible, clear, and
39 meaningful privacy notice that includes all of the following:
40 (1) The categories of personal data processed by the controller.
41 (2) The purpose for processing personal data.
42 (3) How consumers may exercise their consumer rights, including how a
43 consumer may appeal a controller's decision with regard to the consumer's
44 request.
45 (4) The categories of personal data that the controller shares with third parties, if
46 any.
47 (5) The categories of third parties with which the controller shares personal data,
48 if any.
49 (6) An active electronic mail address or other online mechanism that the
50 consumer may use to contact the controller.
