1 (d) If a controller sells personal data to third parties or processes personal data for targeted
2 advertising, the controller shall clearly and conspicuously disclose the processing, as well as the
3 manner in which a consumer may exercise the right to opt out of the processing.
4 (e) A controller shall establish and shall describe in the privacy notice required by
5 subsection (c) of this section one or more secure and reliable means for consumers to submit a
6 request to exercise their consumer rights pursuant to this Chapter. The means shall take into
7 account the ways in which consumers normally interact with the controller, the need for secure
8 and reliable communication of the requests, and the ability of the controller to verify the identity
9 of the consumer making the request. A controller shall not require a consumer to create a new
10 account in order to exercise consumer rights but may require a consumer to use an existing
11 account. Any such means shall include all of the following:
12 (1) Providing a clear and conspicuous link on the controller's internet website to
13 an internet webpage that enables a consumer, or an agent of the consumer, to
14 opt out of the targeted advertising or the sale of the consumer's personal data.
15 (2) Allowing a consumer to opt out of any processing of the consumer's personal
16 data for the purposes of targeted advertising, or any sale of the personal data,
17 through an opt-out preference signal sent, with the consumer's consent, by a
18 platform, technology, or mechanism to the controller indicating the
19 consumer's intent to opt out of any such processing or sale. The platform,
20 technology, or mechanism shall do all of the following:
21 a. Not unfairly disadvantage another controller.
22 b. Not make use of a default setting but, rather, require the consumer to
23 make an affirmative, freely given, and unambiguous choice to opt out
24 of any processing of the consumer's personal data pursuant to this
25 Chapter.
26 c. Be consumer-friendly and easy to use by the average consumer.
27 d. Be as consistent as possible with any other similar platform,
28 technology, or mechanism required by any federal or State law or
29 regulation.
30 e. Enable the controller to reasonably determine whether the consumer
31 is a resident of the State and whether the consumer has made a
32 legitimate request to opt out of any sale of the consumer's personal
33 data or targeted advertising.
34 If a consumer's decision to opt out of any processing of the consumer's personal data for the
35 purposes of targeted advertising, or any sale of the personal data, through an opt-out preference
36 signal sent in accordance with the provisions of subdivision (1) of this subsection conflicts with
37 the consumer's existing controller-specific privacy setting or voluntary participation in a
38 controller's bona fide loyalty, rewards, premium features, discounts, or club card program, the
39 controller shall comply with the consumer's opt-out preference signal but may notify the
40 consumer of the conflict and provide to the consumer the choice to confirm the controller-specific
41 privacy setting or participation in the program.
42 If a controller responds to consumer opt‐out requests received pursuant to subdivision (1) of
43 this subsection by informing the consumer of a charge for the use of any product or service, the
44 controller shall present the terms of any financial incentive offered pursuant to subdivision (2) of
45 this subsection for the retention, use, sale, or sharing of the consumer's personal data.
46 "§ 75F-107. Duties of processors.
47 (a) A processor shall adhere to the instructions of a controller and shall assist the
48 controller in meeting the controller's obligations under this Chapter. The assistance must include
49 all of the following:
50 (1) Taking into account the nature of processing and the information available to
51 the processor, by appropriate technical and organizational measures, insofar
Page 10 House Bill 462-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 as is reasonably practicable, to fulfill the controller's obligation to respond to
2 consumer rights requests.
3 (2) Taking into account the nature of processing and the information available to
4 the processor, by assisting the controller in meeting the controller's obligations
5 in relation to the security of processing the personal data and in relation to the
6 notification of a breach of security of the system of the processor, in order to
7 meet the controller's obligations.
8 (3) Providing necessary information to enable the controller to conduct and
9 document data protection assessments.
10 (b) A contract between a controller and a processor must govern the processor's data
11 processing procedures with respect to processing performed on behalf of the controller. The
12 contract must be binding and clearly set forth instructions for processing data, the nature and
13 purpose of processing, the type of data subject to processing, the duration of processing, and the
14 rights and obligations of both parties. The contract must also require that the processor do all of
15 the following:
16 (1) Ensure that each person processing personal data is subject to a duty of
17 confidentiality with respect to the data.
18 (2) At the controller's direction, delete or return all personal data to the controller
19 as requested at the end of the provision of services, unless retention of the
20 personal data is required by law.
21 (3) Upon the reasonable request of the controller, make available to the controller
22 all information in its possession necessary to demonstrate the processor's
23 compliance with the obligations in this Chapter.
24 (4) After providing the controller an opportunity to object, engage any
25 subcontractor pursuant to a written contract that requires the subcontractor to
26 meet the obligations of the processor with respect to the personal data.
27 (5) Allow, and cooperate with, reasonable assessments by the controller or the
28 controller's designated assessor, or the processor may arrange for a qualified
29 and independent assessor to conduct an assessment of the processor's policies
30 and technical and organizational measures in support of the obligations under
31 this Chapter, using an appropriate and accepted control standard or framework
32 and assessment procedure for the assessments. The processor shall provide a
33 report of the assessment to the controller upon request.
34 (c) Nothing in this section may be construed to relieve a controller or processor from the
35 liabilities imposed on the controller or processor by virtue of the controller's or processor's role
36 in the processing relationship, as described in this Chapter.
37 (d) Determining whether a person is acting as a controller or processor with respect to a
38 specific processing of data is a fact-based determination that depends upon the context in which
39 personal data is to be processed. A person who is not limited in the person's processing of
40 personal data pursuant to a controller's instructions, or who fails to adhere to the instructions, is
41 a controller and not a processor with respect to a specific processing of data. A processor that
42 continues to adhere to a controller's instructions with respect to a specific processing of personal
43 data remains a processor. If a processor begins, alone or jointly with others, determining the
44 purposes and means of the processing of personal data, the processor is a controller with respect
45 to the processing and may be subject to an enforcement action under this Chapter.
46 "§ 75F-108. Data protection assessments.
47 (a) A controller that controls or processes the data of not less than 100,000 consumers,
48 excluding data controlled or processed solely for the purpose of completing a payment
49 transaction, shall conduct and document, on a regular basis, a data protection assessment for each
50 of the controller's processing activities that presents a heightened risk of harm to a consumer. For
House Bill 462-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the purposes of this section, processing that presents a heightened risk of harm to a consumer
2 includes any of the following:
3 (1) The processing of personal data for the purposes of targeted advertising.
4 (2) The sale of personal data.
5 (3) The processing of personal data for the purposes of profiling, where the
6 profiling presents a reasonably foreseeable risk of any of the following:
7 a. Unfair or deceptive treatment of, or unlawful disparate impact on,
8 consumers.
9 b. Financial, physical, or reputational injury to consumers.
10 c. A physical or other intrusion upon the solitude or seclusion, or the
11 private affairs or concerns, of consumers, where the intrusion would
12 be offensive to a reasonable person.
13 d. Other substantial injury to consumers.
14 (4) The processing of sensitive data.
15 (b) Data protection assessments conducted pursuant to subsection (a) of this section shall
16 identify and weigh the benefits that may flow, directly and indirectly, from the processing to the
17 controller, the consumer, other stakeholders, and the public against the potential risks to the rights
18 of the consumer associated with the processing, as mitigated by safeguards that can be employed
19 by the controller to reduce the risks. The controller shall factor into any such data protection
20 assessment the use of de-identified data and the reasonable expectations of consumers, as well
21 as the context of the processing and the relationship between the controller and the consumer
22 whose personal data will be processed.
23 (c) The Attorney General may require that a controller disclose any data protection
24 assessment that is relevant to an investigation conducted by the Attorney General, and the
25 controller shall make the data protection assessment available to the Attorney General. The
26 Attorney General may evaluate the data protection assessment for compliance with the
27 responsibilities set forth in this Chapter. Data protection assessments must be treated as
28 confidential and are not public records within the meaning of Chapter 132 of the General Statutes.
29 Notwithstanding the foregoing, a controller's data protection assessment may be used in an action
30 to enforce this Chapter. To the extent any information contained in a data protection assessment
31 disclosed to the Attorney General includes and conspicuously identifies information subject to
32 attorney-client privilege or work product protection, the disclosure by itself does not constitute a
33 waiver of the privilege or protection.
34 (d) A single data protection assessment may address a comparable set of processing
35 operations that include similar activities.
36 (e) If a controller conducts a data protection assessment for the purpose of complying
37 with another applicable law or regulation, the data protection assessment shall be deemed to
38 satisfy the requirements established in this section if the data protection assessment is reasonably
39 similar in scope and effect to the data protection assessment that would otherwise be conducted
40 pursuant to this section.
41 (f) Data protection assessment requirements shall apply to processing activities created
42 or generated on or after July 1, 2026, and are not retroactive.
43 "§ 75F-109. De-identified data.
44 (a) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to require a controller or processor to
45 re-identify de-identified data or pseudonymous data, or to maintain data in identifiable form, or
46 collect, obtain, retain, or access any data or technology, in order to be capable of associating an
47 authenticated consumer request with personal data.
48 (b) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to require a controller or processor to
49 comply with an authenticated consumer rights request if all of the following apply:
Page 12 House Bill 462-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The controller is not reasonably capable of associating the request with the
2 personal data or it would be unreasonably burdensome for the controller to
3 associate the request with the personal data.
4 (2) The controller does not use the personal data to recognize or respond to the
5 specific consumer who is the subject of the personal data or associate the
6 personal data with other personal data about the same specific consumer.
7 (3) The controller does not sell the personal data to any third party or otherwise
8 voluntarily disclose the personal data to any third party other than a processor,
9 except as otherwise permitted in this section.
10 (c) The rights afforded under G.S. 75F-104(a)(1) to (4), inclusive, do not apply to
11 pseudonymous data in cases where the controller is able to demonstrate that any information
12 necessary to identify the consumer is kept separately and is subject to effective technical and
13 organizational controls that prevent the controller from accessing the information.
14 (d) A controller that discloses pseudonymous data or de-identified data shall exercise
15 reasonable oversight to monitor compliance with any contractual commitments to which the
16 pseudonymous data or de-identified data is subject and shall take appropriate steps to address
17 any breaches of those contractual commitments. The determination of the reasonableness of the
18 oversight and the appropriateness of contractual enforcement must take into account whether the
19 disclosed data includes data that would be sensitive data if it were re-identified.
20 "§ 75F-110. Exclusions.
21 (a) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to restrict a controller's or processor's
22 ability to do any of the following:
23 (1) Comply with federal, State, or local laws, rules, or regulations.
24 (2) Comply with a civil, criminal, or regulatory inquiry, investigation, subpoena,
25 or summons by federal, State, local, or other governmental authorities.
26 (3) Cooperate with law enforcement agencies concerning conduct or activity that
27 the controller or processor reasonably and in good faith believes may violate
28 federal, State, or local laws, rules, or regulations.
29 (4) Investigate, establish, exercise, prepare for, or defend legal claims.
30 (5) Provide a product or service specifically requested by a consumer.
31 (6) Perform under a contract to which a consumer is a party, including fulfilling
32 the terms of a written warranty.
33 (7) Take steps at the request of a consumer prior to entering into a contract.
34 (8) Take immediate steps to protect an interest that is essential for the life or
35 physical safety of the consumer or another individual and where the
36 processing cannot be manifestly based on another legal basis.
37 (9) Prevent, detect, protect against, or respond to security incidents, identity theft,
38 fraud, harassment, malicious or deceptive activities, or any illegal activity;
39 preserve the integrity or security of systems; or investigate, report, or
40 prosecute those responsible for any such activity.
41 (10) Engage in public or peer-reviewed scientific research in the public interest that
42 adheres to all other applicable ethics and privacy laws and is approved,
43 monitored, and governed by an institutional review board that determines
44 whether the deletion of the information is likely to provide substantial benefits
45 that do not exclusively accrue to the controller, the expected benefits of the
46 research outweigh the privacy risks, and whether the controller has
47 implemented reasonable safeguards to mitigate privacy risks associated with
48 research, including any risks associated with re-identification.
49 (11) Assist another controller, processor, or third party with any of the activities
50 under this subsection.
House Bill 462-First Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) The obligations imposed on controllers or processors under this Chapter, other than
2 those imposed by G.S. 75F-109, do not restrict a controller's or processor's ability to collect data
3 directly from consumers, or use or retain the data, for internal use only, to do any of the following:
4 (1) Conduct internal research to develop, improve, or repair products, services, or
5 technology.
6 (2) Effectuate a product recall.
7 (3) Identify and repair technical errors that impair existing or intended
8 functionality.
9 (4) Perform internal operations that are reasonably aligned with the expectations
10 of the consumer or reasonably anticipated based on the consumer's existing
11 relationship with the controller or are otherwise compatible with processing
12 data in furtherance of the provision of a product or service specifically
13 requested by a consumer or the performance of a contract to which the
14 consumer is a party.
15 (c) The obligations imposed on controllers or processors under this Chapter shall not
16 apply where compliance by the controller or processor with said sections would violate an
17 evidentiary privilege under the laws of this State. Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to
18 prevent a controller or processor from providing personal data concerning a consumer to a person
19 covered by an evidentiary privilege under the laws of this State as part of a privileged
20 communication.
21 (d) A controller or processor that discloses personal data to a processor or third-party
22 controller in compliance with this Chapter shall not be deemed to have violated said sections if
23 the processor or third-party controller that receives and processes the personal data violates said
24 sections, provided that (i) at the time the disclosing controller or processor disclosed the personal
25 data, the disclosing controller or processor did not have actual knowledge that the receiving
26 processor or third-party controller had violated or would violate said sections and (ii) the
27 disclosing controller or processor was, and remained, in compliance with its obligations as the
28 discloser of the data hereunder. A third-party controller or processor receiving personal data from
29 a controller or processor in compliance with this Chapter is likewise not in violation of said
30 sections for the independent misconduct of the controller or processor from which the third-party
31 controller or processor receives the personal data.
32 (e) Nothing in this Chapter may be construed to do any of the following:
33 (1) Impose any obligation on a controller or processor that adversely affects the
34 rights of any person to freedom of speech or freedom of the press guaranteed
35 by the First Amendment to the United States Constitution or Article I, Section
36 14 of the North Carolina Constitution.
37 (2) Apply to any person's processing of personal data in the course of the person's
38 purely personal or household activities.
39 (f) Personal data processed pursuant to this section may be processed to the extent that
40 the processing is reasonably necessary and proportionate to the purposes listed in this section and
41 is adequate, relevant, and limited to what is necessary in relation to the specific purposes listed
42 in this section. Personal data collected, used, or retained pursuant to subsection (b) of this section
43 shall, where applicable, take into account the nature and purpose or purposes of the collection,
44 use, or retention. The data shall be subject to reasonable administrative, technical, and physical
45 measures to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and accessibility of the personal data and to
46 reduce reasonably foreseeable risks of harm to consumers relating to the collection, use, or
47 retention of personal data.
48 (g) If a controller processes personal data pursuant to an exemption in this section, the
49 controller bears the burden of demonstrating that the processing qualifies for the exemption and
50 complies with the requirements of subsection (f) of this section.
