General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (h) Processing personal data for the purposes expressly identified in this section shall not
2 solely make a legal entity a controller with respect to the processing.
3 "§ 75F-111. Enforcement.
4 (a) The Department of Justice shall investigate and enforce alleged violations of this
5 Chapter.
6 (b) The Department of Justice may, prior to initiating any action for a violation of any
7 provision of this Chapter, issue a notice of violation to the controller or processor if the
8 Department of Justice determines that a cure is possible. If the Department of Justice issues a
9 notice of violation, the controller shall have at least 60 days to cure the violation after receipt of
10 the notice. If the controller fails to cure the violation within the time period, the Department of
11 Justice may bring an enforcement proceeding pursuant to subsection (a) of this section. In
12 determining whether to grant a controller or processor an opportunity to cure an alleged violation,
13 the Department of Justice may consider all of the following:
14 (1) The number of violations.
15 (2) The size and complexity of the controller or processor.
16 (3) The nature and extent of the controller's or processor's processing activities.
17 (4) The substantial likelihood of injury to the public.
18 (5) The safety of persons or property.
19 (6) Whether the alleged violation was likely caused by human or technical error.
20 (7) The extent to which the controller or processor has violated this or similar
21 laws in the past.
22 (c) Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed as providing the basis for, or be subject to,
23 a private right of action for violations of said sections or any other law.
24 (d) A violation of this Chapter shall be deemed an unfair practice under G.S. 75-1.1."
25 SECTION 1.3. Beginning at least six months prior to the effective date of this act,
26 the Department of Justice shall engage in public outreach to educate consumers and the business
27 community about this act.
