29 PART II. ENACT SOCIAL MEDIA SAFETY ACT
30 SECTION 2.1. Effective January 1, 2026, the General Statutes are amended by
31 adding a new Chapter to read:
32 "Chapter 75G.
33 "Social Media Verification.
34 "§ 75G-101. Definitions.
35 The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
36 (1) Account holder. – An individual who creates an account or a profile to use a
37 social media platform.
38 (2) Commercial entity. – A corporation, limited liability company, partnership,
39 limited partnership, sole proprietorship, or other legally recognized entity. The
40 term includes a third-party vendor.
41 (3) Digitized identification card. – A data file available on a mobile device that
42 has connectivity to the internet through a State-approved application that
43 allows the mobile device to download the data file from the Division of Motor
44 Vehicles that contains all of the data elements visible on the face and back of
45 a drivers license or identification card and displays the current status of the
46 drivers license or identification card, including valid, expired, cancelled,
47 suspended, revoked, active, or inactive.
48 (4) Minor. – An individual under 18 years of age.
49 (5) North Carolina user. – An individual who is a resident of the State of North
50 Carolina and who accesses or attempts to access a social media platform while
51 present in this State by accessing the social media platform while using a
House Bill 462-First Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 North Carolina Internet Protocol address or otherwise known or believed to
2 be in this State while using the social media platform.
3 (6) Reasonable age verification. – To confirm that a person seeking to access a
4 social media platform is at least 18 years old.
5 (7) Social media company. – An online forum that a company makes available
6 for an account holder to:
7 a. Create a public profile, establish an account, or register as a user for
8 the primary purpose of interacting socially with other profiles and
9 accounts;
10 b. Upload or create posts or content;
11 c. View posts or content of other account holders; and
12 d. Interact with other account holders or users, including, without
13 limitation, establishing mutual connections through request and
14 acceptance.
15 (7a) Social media company. – Does not include any of the following:
16 a. A company that exclusively offers subscription content in which users
17 follow or subscribe unilaterally and whose platforms' primary purpose
18 is not social interaction.
19 b. A social media company that allows a user to generate short video
20 clips of dancing, voice overs, or other acts of entertainment in which
21 the primary purpose is not educational or informative does not meet
22 the exclusion under sub-subdivision a. of this subdivision.
23 c. A media company that exclusively offers interactive gaming, virtual
24 gaming, or an online service; that allows the creation and uploading of
25 content for the purpose of interactive gaming, entertainment, or
26 associated entertainment; and the communication related to that
27 content.
28 d. A company that offers cloud storage services, enterprise cybersecurity
29 services, educational devices, or enterprise collaboration tools for
30 kindergarten through grade 12 (K-12) schools and derives less than
31 twenty-five percent (25%) of the company's revenue from operating a
32 social media platform, including games and advertising.
33 e. A company that provides career development opportunities, including
34 professional networking, job skills, learning certifications, and job
35 posting and application services.
36 (8) Social media platform. – A public or semipublic internet-based service or
37 application that has users in North Carolina and on which a substantial
38 function of the service or application is to connect users in order to allow users
39 to interact socially with each other within the service or application; however,
40 a service or application that provides email or direct messaging shall not be
41 considered to be a social media platform on the basis of that function alone.
42 (8a) Social media platform. – Does not include an online service, a website, or an
43 application if the predominant or exclusive function is:
44 a. Electronic mail.
45 b. Direct messaging consisting of messages, photos, or videos that are
46 sent between devices by electronic means if messages are:
47 1. Shared between the sender and the recipient or recipients;
48 2. Only visible to the sender and the recipient or recipients; and
49 3. Are not posted publicly.
50 c. A streaming service that (i) provides only licensed media in a
51 continuous flow from the service, website, or application to the end
Page 16 House Bill 462-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 user and (ii) does not obtain a license to the media from a user or
2 account holder by agreement of the streaming service's terms of
3 service.
4 d. News, sports, entertainment, or other content that is preselected by the
5 provider and not user generated, including, without limitation, if any
6 chat, comment, or interactive functionality that is provided is
7 incidental to, directly related to, or dependent upon provision of the
8 content.
9 e. Online shopping or e-commerce, if the interaction with other users or
10 account holders is generally limited to:
11 1. The ability to post and comment on reviews;
12 2. The ability to display lists or collections of goods for sale or
13 wish lists; and
14 3. Other functions that are focused on online shopping or
15 e-commerce rather than interaction between users or account
16 holders.
17 f. Business-to-business software that is not accessible to the general
18 public.
19 g. Cloud storage.
20 h. Shared document collaboration.
21 i. Providing access to or interacting with data visualization platforms,
22 libraries, or hubs.
23 j. To permit comments on a digital news website, if the news content is
24 posted only by the provider of the digital news website.
25 k. For the purpose of providing or obtaining technical support for the
26 social media company's social media platform, products, or services.
27 l. Academic or scholarly research.
28 m. Other research if (i) the majority of the content is posted or created by
29 the provider of the online service, website, or application and (ii) the
30 ability to chat, comment, or interact with other users is directly related
31 to the provider's content; then, the following criteria must also apply:
32 1. The service is a classified advertising service that only permits
33 the sale of goods and prohibits the solicitation of personal
34 services or that is used by and under the direction of an
35 educational entity, including, without limitation, a learning
36 management system, student engagement program, and
37 subject-specific or skill-specific program.
38 (8b) Social media platform. – Does not include a social media platform that is
39 controlled by a business entity that has generated less than one hundred
40 million dollars ($100,000,000) in annual gross revenue.
41 (9) User. – A person who has access to view all or some of the posts and content
42 on a social media platform but is not an account holder.
43 "§ 75G-102. Social media platforms; reasonable age verification methods; parental consent
44 required.
45 (a) A social media company shall not permit a North Carolina user who is a minor to be
46 an account holder on the social media company's social media platform unless the minor has the
47 express consent of a parent or legal guardian. A social media company shall verify the age of an
48 account holder. If an account holder is a minor, the social media company shall confirm that a
49 minor has consent under this subsection to become a new account holder at the time a North
50 Carolina user opens the account.
House Bill 462-First Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) A social media company shall use a third-party vendor to perform reasonable age
2 verification before allowing access to the social media company's social media platform.
3 (c) Reasonable age verification methods under this section include providing one of the
4 following:
5 (1) A digitized identification card, including a digital copy of a drivers license
6 issued by the Division of Motor Vehicles.
7 (2) Government-issued identification.
8 (3) Any commercially reasonable age verification method.
9 "§ 75G-103. Liability for social media companies.
10 (a) A social media company that knowingly violates this Chapter is liable if the social
11 media company fails to perform a reasonable age verification.
12 (b) If a social media company performs a reasonable age verification, the social media
13 company shall not retain any identifying information of the individual after access to the social
14 media platform has been granted.
15 (c1) Violation of G.S. 75G-102 is a Class 1 misdemeanor. As authorized under this
16 section, the district attorney for the county where the North Carolina user resides may initiate a
17 criminal proceeding against a social media company that allegedly violates G.S. 75G-102.
18 (c2) As authorized under G.S. 75G-104, the Attorney General may initiate a civil
19 enforcement action against a social media company that allegedly commits a violation of
20 G.S. 75G-102.
21 (c3) A social media company that violates this Chapter is liable to an individual for:
22 (1) A penalty of two thousand five hundred dollars ($2,500) per violation, court
23 costs, and reasonable attorneys' fees as ordered by the court; or
24 (2) Damages resulting from a minor accessing a social media platform without
25 his or her parent's or custodian's consent, including court costs and reasonable
26 attorneys' fees as ordered by the court.
27 (d) This section does not:
28 (1) Apply to a news or public interest broadcast, website video, report, or event;
29 (2) Affect the rights of a news-gathering organization; or
30 (3) Apply to cloud service providers.
31 (e) An internet service provider, or any of its affiliates or subsidiaries, or search engines
32 shall not violate this Chapter solely by providing access, connection to or from a website, or other
33 information or content on the internet, or a facility, system, or network that is not under that
34 internet service provider's control, including transmission, downloading, intermediate storage,
35 access software, or other service that provides access or connectivity, to the extent the internet
36 service provider is not responsible for the creation of the content or the communication on a
37 social media platform.
38 "§ 75G-104. Liability for commercial entity or third-party vendor.
39 (a) A commercial entity or third-party vendor shall not retain any identifying information
40 of an individual after access to the social media platform has been granted.
41 (b) A commercial entity that is found to have knowingly retained identifying information
42 of an individual after access to the material is granted is liable to the individual for damages
43 resulting from the retention of the identifying information, including court costs and reasonable
44 attorneys' fees as ordered by the court."
45
46 PART III. SEVERABILITY
47 SECTION 3.1. If any provision of this act or the application thereof to any person
48 or circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity does not affect any other provision or application
49 of the act which can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to that end,
50 the provisions of this act are declared to be severable.
